{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_frenchbulldog_ver04/data/sn83045433/00280764140/1921021501/0693.xml":{"full_text":"0)e\ni J|asf)ington J-lcr^alt)\nFii^'shed Every Morning in the Year by\nThe Washington Herald Company,\n435-427-429 Eleventh St. Washington, D. C.\nJ. E. RICE President and Geneial Manager\nPhone: Main 3300?All Departments\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES?BY CARRIER\nf. In Washington and Vi.-inity\nDaily and Sunday, 1 Moi;th. 60c; 1 Year. $7 20\nSUBSCRIPTION BY MAIL IN ADVANCE\nDaily and Sunday, 1 Month, 65c; 1 Year. $7 50Daily\nOnly, 1 Month, 50c; 1 Year, $6.00\nMember of Ike Audit Bureau of Circulations\nADVERTISING REPRESENTATIVES:\nThe Beckiuith Special Agency\nNew York, World Building; Chicago. Tribune\nBuilding; St. Louis, Post-Dispatch Building: Detroit,\nFord Building; Kansas City. Mo., Bryant\nBuilding; Atlanta, Ga.. 1415 Atlanta Trust Building\nTUESDAY, FEBRUARY 15, 1921.\nThere is no theam more plentiful! to scan\nThan is the glorious goodly frame of man.\n?Du Bartas.\nReturn of Prosperity.\nTHE United States is the richcst country in the\nworld in bulk wealth. It is of vastly more\nimportance that it, also, leads the world in\nthe. even distribution of this bulk wealth among its\npeople. It is the country of the high average of\nthe purchasing power of its people.\nThe social and industrial system here is so organized\nthat any marked increase in prosperous conditions\nis reflected through the entire population.\nWhen^t is declared that liquidation or depression\nhas pa*?ed the low point and conditions are recovering,\n\"that prosperity is returning, this does not\nmean tor the few, but for the many.\nDepression always comes first to financial circles\nand the producers of raw materials. They arc the\nfirst to be hit. It is nearly a year since the consumers\nbegan a sort of retail boycott, they stopped\nbuying. It was a latter consequence that the banks\nwere ordered to curtail credits. The machinerythen\nbegan to slow up.\nLiquidation forced by these conditions, followed.\nWholesale prices fell until there has been a cut of\n35 to 50 per cent. The retailers' price-slashing has\nfollowed and all authorities now declare stabilization\nhas begun where depression began. Confidence\nJ? returning. The outlook is bright.\nThis does not mean higher prices to the consumer.\nIt means, on the contrary, that the lower\nlevel Will continue and that the user has resumed\nbuying on this assured low price basis. Permanency\nJs the keynote.\nWhat are some facts which show the absolute\nsoundness of American conditions? In 19.20 five\nstaple farm crops made new production records.\nThe corn crop was 130,000,000 bushels above the\nprevious high record in 1917. Rice exceeded the\nrecord by 1,000,000 bushels; tobacco by 70.000,000\npounds; sugar beets by 1,100,000.000 pounds; sweet\netatoes by 7,000,000 bushels; oats by 70,000,000\nbushels; wheat and rye did not reach the high mark,\nbut rye doubled the prewar crop and wheat was\nwell over 100,000,000 more than 1916 and 1917.\nWhat was true of crops was in large measure\ntrue 01 minerals. Petroleum production increased\n70,000,000 barrels; coal was less than 5 per cent\nbelow lyiy; copper exceeded 1919, as did pig iron\nby several million tons.\nIt must be remembered that all real wealth\ncomes from the land in these two forms of foods\nand minerals. It is in these forms mo^t widely\ntlistributed. It goes directly into purchasing power.\nWheat alone added $9,148,000,000 to the national\nwealth and while the farmers did not get a price\nequal to that of 1919. they got over $3,000,000,000\nI more than for the prewar crops. What was the\nr fact as to wheat was true in proportion as to\ncotton.\nThe farmers as producers of raw materials\nwere with the holders of stocks and bonds, the capItalisH,\nfirst to t'eej the pressure of liquidation. But\nthey face ioji with lower prices for what they buy\nan4 will come to the harvest with a lower labor\nI tost.\nAll of this is encouraging; none of it is discouraging.\nIt all points to recovery; to good times;\nj\" to prosperity. There is no room for the glooms;\nfor continued depression; for more than the temporal^\nperiod of price transition, in a country which\nlias annually poured into it storehouses such an\nenormous amount ot broadly distributed new\nwealth.\nMr. Dawes has his own opinions and is\nwilling to express them with trimmings to any\nbtankety-blank Congressman who asks for\ntliem.\nLet the Dead Bury Their Dead.\n-It makes little difference to the world of today\nwhat the former Kaiser thinks about anything. It\nIs a matter of indifference as affecting world affalrj\nwhether or not he is reconciled to his exile;\nwhather or not he willed the war; or what his personal\nopinion is a? to the causes of German defeat.\n^The recent interview with him published in The\nHerald, is interesting as the reflex of a human oddijy\nAs such he always had this same interest to\nstudents or analyists of human character. He is\nno more unique in exile than in power and his judgment\nhas ?o more value; it merely has less weight\nor fonsequence.\nr Nor has he become a \"religious fanatic.\" He\nnever was and never will be a religious anything,\nother than a formalist. He has always been consumed\nby his own too-much. He has suffered from\nan ingrown and badly distorted ego. That sort of a\nman is always a physical and moral coward.\nIt is but significant of thi* that he now blames\nGerman defeat on \"my people' who \"have betrayed\nthemselves, their God and me.\" He blames everybody\nand everything but himself. Because of this\nbetrayal \"God scourges the world;\" he himself is\ninnocent, he has but been betrayed, and his partner\nis evening accounts for hint.\niHe pleads guilty to cowardly weakness when\nhe excuses himself for beginning the war as he does\nfor losing it. He says: \"The sword of peace was\nstruck out1 of my hand by my best friends.\" That\nsort of a hand has no business fooling with a sword.\n\"This same absence of strength, of couragc, of\ndecision followed him through the war. He was\nnot a leader; he did not inspire his armies; he was\nrJJ a?' ^n8cri he wa* always double\nguarded, and was rightly estimated by those in\ncommand who knew him best.\nThe world can now best serve itself by forgetting\nhim. I|e should be dropped from memory.\nHe should be left to dry rot in his living grave. He\nis of no consequence. \"In power he was a constant\nmenace. Buf the old order in Germany has passed\nforever and he has gone with it. He simply is not\nyet buried.\nMr. Harding has been surrounded in\nFlorida by real friends. He caught the largest\nfish.\nMysterious Process of Disarmament.\nCongress is fully committed to* the policy of\ndisarmament. It is recognized that there is a national\ndemand for this. Probably the United States\ncan stand the cost of huge armaments, but the\npeople have revolt?d against this cost and against\n'he principle of a ^reat armed establishment.\nIt is fully realized, also, that even if this country\ncan stand the tax, 110 other country can. It is as\nfully realized that the quickest and surest way to\neconomic soundness and world buying power is\nthrough disarmament. This people want the money\n?now spent by foreign governments in armies and\nnavies used, to put it sordidly, in the purchase of\nour products and payment of debts due.\nCongress heard Sir Phillips Gibbs and appreciates\nthat he spoke truly when he said: \"The\nLnitcd States pays the piper and she has the right\nto call the tune. If she calls the tune of peace,\nthe nations of the world will rise up and dance\nto it.\"\nSo it has cut the army to 175,000 men and gone\n011 record for the greatest navy in the world centered\naround capital ships at a cost of around $50,000,000\neach. It is rightly argued that this country\ndoes not need a great army for a few years, as it\nhas now 4,000,000 men trained in the great war.\nThree thousand miles from any possible foe, all\nj that i<r needed just now for defensive or offensive\nwar, is the greatest navy in the world. With a\nhandful of foreign coast line, as compared to Great\nj Britain, we must have as great a navy. With no\n1 mandatories when she has a half dozen or more, still\nwe must have as great a navy.\nRoosevelt said we did not need as great a navy\nas that of Great Britain. But he is dead and does\nnot know the present processes of disarmament.\nMe cannot know the force of this national demand\nand the devious ways essential to compliance\nvi ith it.\nOf course it must be conceded that if the United\nStates must have the greatest navy, France must\nsurely have the greatest army and no other European\ncountry should fail to have a large military\nestablishment, not for offense, oh, no, only as is our\ngreatest navy, for defense.\nT he Lord is said to work in mysterious ways,\nHis wonders to perform. But at that he has nothing\non Congress in its plan for disarmament.\nThe man who used to be able to drink just\nenough, but never too much, is no longer able\nto do even that.\nFound an Egg.\nAnother mimmoth mare's nest has been uncovered\nup on Capitol Hill. In it is an egg of unusual\ndimensions. It was never hatched, but bears the\nname which has become familiar as disclosing the\nproprietary right in such cruit crops?Woodrow\nWilson.\nIt was first discovered that Great Britain had\nsuggested to this government the mutual cancellation\nof foreign debts. That was bad enough. But\nthis egg shows that President Wilson at the time of\nthe peace negotiations, promised to recommend this,\nif the Senate ratified the treaty with the league of\nnations covenant.\nThe f oreign Relation? Committee of the Senate\nis now said to have known of this all the time.\nV\\ ith admirable self-restraint they refrained from\nmaking it public, not to save Mr. Wilson from impeachment\nor something worse, but to save the informant\nfrom having to deny that he ever told it,\nas official ethics would have compelled him to lie\nabout it.\n)f course a great many good intentioned and\npatriotic, even if mistaken, Americans have advo,\ncated this very tiling. They have been of both parties\nand as to the French debt, have had a very considerable\nfollowing. Of course also the debts due\nJ the I nited States could be cancelled only by act of\nCongress. Of course, too, the ratifying of the\ntreaty and covenant would have had no possible\nrelation to any such fiscal action.\nOf course 110 one positively knows if Mr. Wilson\ndid or did not honor his heart, if not his head,\nby any such actual promise. Neither is it intimated\nthat he did this as binding'in any sense upon\nCongress, or as pledging Congressional action.\nWould it not be just as well if Congress\nbuckled down to business without having Wilsonian\nnightmares every fifteen miutes and without keying\ntheir temperamenlal proclivities so to the Wilson\npitch.\nI here was a President not long ago who lost\nout by listening to those who told him he must first1\nof all avoid all his predecessor had done, advocated,\nthought or planned. He must go in the opposite\ndirection. Strangely enough, no official can simply\ndo what is right and best, by merely not doing\nanything some one else who preceded him in office\nhas done, thought or favored, or by doing the\nopposite.\nEinstein has a far easier job than Mr.\nHarding. He only has to develop new hypotheses,\nand leave them for others to disprove.\nHe Had No Dog.\nIt is rather amusing, not to say pitiful to have\nso thrilling a story as that of the awful conduct\nof the colored troops in the French occupied German\nterritory, punctured. The crimes of the men\nfrom North Africa was duly horrifying.\nOur Congress was to be asked to demand' that\nthe French withdraw them. Americans were to be\nso shocked that they would take upon themselves\nthis obligation of humanity. They were to be arrayed\non behalf of terrorized German womankind.\nJust then Secretary of State Colby issued a\nformal statement that there were no Senegalese\namong the French troops of occupation and had\nnot been for some time. During the period of\nthese complaints, the black men were conspicuous\nby their absence.\nIt is all very much like the case of the farmer\na[7JStedJ0rJk\"Ping a cross dog ,hat had bitten a\nchild. His defense was that his dog was harmless.\nthat it was a kind dog, that it was too old to bite\nanyone, that it had no teeth, and finally that he did\nnot have anfr never had had a dog.\nThe Leviathan is just a huge stomach with\nan insatiable appetite.\ntfefrll if Vj i'i\n-Tk Gtv'i Guwti T?ll\n/ft WK?i the Natioo\nCw^flP.\nI YOINU WOHKKFIS\nGAINED THE VICTORY.\n\"After all, it was the 'pep* of tl><\nyoung workers of the Nationa\nWoman's Party that put the nine\nteenth amendment over, and il\nwould be a pity to abandon th<\nefficient human machine thai wai\nbuilt up during the fight for worn\nan's suffrage,\" says Miss Gai\nLaughlln, San Francisco lawyer ant\nveteran worker for equal suffrage\nwho arrived in Washington yester\nday for the first annual conventloi\nof the Natlonal%Woman's Party.\nThere would be no question as t<\nthe advisability of retaining th<\npresent organization as a vehicle fo'\nfurther work in bettering the statu:\nof women throughout the worl<\nwere it not for the avowed inten\nti6n of Miss Alice Paul to with\ndraw from the active chairmanshi]\nof the party which she built up, according\nto Miss I^aughltp.\nMiss I>aughlin. who is a membe\nof the California Republican :it<\nCentral Committee anfl who workec\nfor suffrage both in Colorado and 11\nCalifornia knows the history of tin\nfeminist movement in this countr:\nas few others.\nOne of the first of the moderi\nschool of American feminists. Mis\nLaughlln is a graduate of Wellesle:\nCollege and holds a degree from th<\nLaw School of Cornell University\nShe was here in Washington twentj\nyears ago. serving under McKinle:\nas'expert agent of the United Statei\nIndustrial Commission.\nCALIFORNIA WOMK\\\nGAIN Sl'PREHACV.\nComplete equality of women with\nmen before the law is now one o\nthe greatest needs in this country\nin the opinion of Miss Laughlin,\nwho was the author of the progressive\njury laws in California which\npermit women to serve on juries\nwith men. These laws have beer\nin operation several years, she says\nand have been highly successful\nShe is also the author of the com*\nmunity property bill and other advanced\nmeasures, either already or\nthe California statute books oi\nabout to become laws. The positior\nof women in California is much bet\nter than before suffrage was\ngranted, she says. California worn\nen have been able to improve theii\nlegal status since they gained the\nvote, she says.\nMiss Laughlin. who is a councillor\nof Wellesley College, points\nwith satisfaction to the improvet\nstanding of women in the institutions\nof higher learning in this\ncountry, where they are now received\non practically the same\nfooting as men.\n\"There was a time and within mj\nrecollection when a woman had tc\ninako a hard fight to enter the pro\nfejjsions In this country, but now\nhappily, all this is changed.\" saif\nMiss Laughlin.\nThe number of women serving or\nthe faculties of coeducational colleges\nshould be increased, but Mis.'\nLaughlin believes thaf the dlspar\ntty is gradually diminishing.\nShe points to the University ol\nCalifornia as presenting evidence\nof the tendency toward equalizint\nthis difference. The woman's clut\nof the faculty of this university\nnow has eighty members, she says.\nSuffrage was granted the womei\nof California by th\" !eglsla'uro ;i\n1911. When the California Civi\nleague was organized in 1012 f??\nthe promotion -?f the interests\nthe women of the State and wit1\nthe object of acquainting the newlj\nenfranchised citizens with th?\nrights and responsibilities. Mis'\nLaughlin was etcct? d presu1* nt\nthe organization servin,; in thu\ncapacity for seveni yeais.\nYVo'.ien are n< w t.'kin* in a< t;vi\npa-t it. til* political life ?f >ne St:i?tiie\nsavs. Three w >m^n hre nov\nin the legislature; a woman hold\nthe oftiee of district attorney o\nAlameda County, which lies jus\nacross the bay from San Francisco\nanother. Miss Grace Catikin. has a?\nadministrative position with th<\nFederal Land Office in San Francis\nco. Throughout the State, wome?\nare serving on boards and commis\nsions and there are several wonvi\nj justices of the peace. Mrs. An\nnette Adams. ?ho came to Wash\nI incton as Assistant Attorney Gen\nI eral of the United States, is a r*p\nresentative California professiona\nwoman\nu FIRST PRK!?IDKNT\nOF NATIONAL FKDKIIATION.\nMiss Laughlln was the first pres\nident of the National Federation o\nBusiness and Professional Women\nhaving been elected at the first\nconvention of the organisation, heli\nin St. Louis .in 101f>. She stumpe*\nfor suffrage for four years and\nhalf, and during the .war was onof\nthe \"Four-minute men.\" Mlsi\nLaughlln holds many offices ot\nboards and commissions, and is\ndirector of the New England So\nciety of Wellesley College. She ii\nalso* an officer in the California\nFederation of Women's Clubs, t\nmember of the bar of the State o!\nCalifornia and a member of th<\nAssociate Collegiate Alumni. During\nthe war she organized and di\nrected the California branch of th<\nNational League for Woman's Service.\nQuestioned with respect to hei\nattitude on disarmament and worlc\npeace. Miss laughlln says that sh?\nis opposed to war fundamentals\nas arc many other good people, bu\nthat she does not believe that th?\nUnited States or any other natior\nshould lay down Its arms until al\nthe rest of the world does.\n\"1 am a pacificist In so far as\nbelieve with many others that wai\nis a terrible and unnecessary sac\nrlflce of human life,\" she sa|jl. \"bui\nif it came to a choice betweer\npeace and honor and justice, I woulc\nchoose war. I think that we should\nhave gone Into the recent war Ions\nbefore we did. If I could have hac\nmy way we should have gone 1*\nthe moment the Lusltanla wai\nsunk.\"\nThe Japanese question Is stil\nacute In California, according t*\nMiss Laughlln, who hopes that th<\npeople of the fcast will awaken t(\nthe reality of the peril whirl\nmenaces the white people of th<\nState.\n'It is a problem which In mj\nestimation is far more difficult ol\nsolution than the colored problen\nin the Bouth,\" she explained, \"foi\nthe Japanese are proud, amhltloui\nand tricky. It Is a constant batth\nof wits between the Japanese* anr\nthe whites, for they will aval\nthomselves-of any possible sub\\er\nfuge or legal technicality to In\nsinuate where they an\nnot wanted.\"\nMiss l*auffhlln will return t?\nCalifornia upon the conclusion?oi\nthe convention.\nF. W. O.\n\nMaybe It's Just at Wei\nAfter All for Purely\nTHE last\"\n\n\nScientific\nNotes and\nComment\nCalendar of .Heelings;\nActivities of Societies\nIn Washington\n\nColombia H1st orient Socleiy, ??m?,\nclub. this evening. 8:15 o'clock\nI \"The Pounding of an Astronomical\nObsfrvatory in Washington,\" by\nI>r. Charles O. I'auliin\n?HOttT \\-R\\VS l-'OH CA *CKR\nNOT \\KW I1ISCOVKRV.\nI.o.al scientists and physicians,\ncommenting on the artlcic puh(\nlished yesterday on the \"discovery\"\nt \"t X-rays of very high penetrating\npower by Prof. William Duane, of\nHarvard, declared last night that\nL such rays, the laws governing them.\ns and their therapeutic use have been\nf known for some years. Many sclcnI\n?ists and physicians in laboratories\nof her than at Harvard have been\nexperimenting with the X-rays of,\np *er.v short length that are produced I\nby ver\\ high voltages In the vac\nlum tube. Tt is these waves of\n-rreater frequency that are nearly\n'h-- same as the gamma rrys that\njrc given off from radium and that\nhave the very great penetration\nThat the news dispatch from I'jmbndgc\nis simply a summary of the\nwork that has been done in tile\noast, is rh*' opinion of those i?,\nformed on the subject.\nAt least three local laboratories\nire using these very short X-rays\nin the t reament of cancer, according\nto a local radiologist seen last\nf night. While a|| (his work is in the\ndevelopment stage, jt reported\nt '-hat in several instances casj-s that\ni were considered inoperable and\n1 hopeless a year ago are now alive\n>nd evidently improving.\nIt was pointed out that as the\nradium supply is limited and cx1\npensive. X-rays of this kind may\nt be the means of savin* those who\ncannot be tre^ed with radium.\nHowever, radium Is much easier to\napply to the cancer, and while the\nt first cost is great. t}>e^>nlv subser\nquent expense Is the interest on\nk the Investment.\nrSK OF H4RMOXIC\nMATHKMATHH VKRIF,\nHow the harmonic 'mathematics\nseries are used in problems of\nphysics was told by Dr. D. R. Harper\nat the Mathematics Club riVeetins\nat the Bureau of Standards yesj\nterday afternoon.\n\"Harmonic series embrace those\nmathematical functions Which have\nJ properties somewhat similar to\nthose of the ordinary trigonometric\nsine and cosine.\" he said, \"and they\nwere so named because acoustic\nharmonics are represented mathemMically\nby the sine and cosine\ncurves.\" He suggested how this se\nrles can be tjjed In potential, gravitational\nor electric problems, and\nrroblems of thermal conduction, and\nI vibration of strings, drums and bars.\nrwrun mortality on\nll*CRKA*K, SAY DOCTOR!).\nThat cancer mortality is on the\nIncrease at the rate of 2>4 per cent\na yar, and that the death rate due\nlo this disease has practically\ndoubled .in the last forty years are\nfacts that were brought out at the\nlast meeting of the Medical Society.\nAt the saem time, infant mortality.\ndeaths from tuberculosis and other\ndiseases are gradually decreasing\nOver 90,000 deaths per year occur\nr In this country because of cancer/it\nwas estimated.\nMortality Increase is occurring In\nEngland as well as America, accord1\ning to statistics compiled by health\nauthorities and insurance companies\nan* physicians arc at a loss for an\nexplanation.\nEarly treatment and Identification\nof cancer were urged, and doctors\nwere told that undue optimism\nshould not .replace careful lamination\nof indefinite early aymsiojns. In\n1 to Go on and finish I\nDomestic Purposes.?E\nSt\nip^?N\nLWf^!\nQ\\^\nFive 'Lame Ducks'\nAdmitted to D. C.\nBar Association\nThr names of five more \"lame\nducks\" who will, to a more or less\nextent. make Washington their\nheadquarters after March 4. were\nadded yesterday to the ever-growing\nlist of men onto prominent in\n.public life who now maintain law\noffices here.\nThe names went on the list when\nAttorney General A. Mitchell Pa!-\nmer. Assistant Attorney General\nFrank Davis, jr.. Senator Hoke\nSmith, of Georgia; Representative\nScott Ferris, of Oklahoma, and <iraham\nEdgerton. solicitor of the Navy\nDepartment, were sworn in yesterday\nby the District Supreme Court\nin general term as members of the\ni District of Columbia Bar Association.\nHear Admiral Samuel McGowan.\nformer Pa\\maM?r Genera! of the\nNavy, was also sworn in as a member.\nTW ELVE ADMITTED\nTO TRADE BOARD\nTwelve applicants were admitted\nto membership in the Hoard of Trade\nat a meeting of the executive committee\nyesterday.\nK. C. Graham, vice chairman of\nthe committee, presided, in the absence\nof Chairman Samuel J. Prescott.\nFollowing are the names of\nthe new members: C. M. Towers. G.\nThyson. jr.: John W. Oehmann. Edmund\nO. Carl. Charles R. Mcf'oy.\nJames W. Lyon*. L. C. Deich. Jam* 5\nHowell Gordon. George Perkins, Ren\nF. Young. Charles T. Felter and\nGeorge Briggs Colbeck.\nOil Fever Hits Canada.\nThe Canadian land office is again\nbein^ besieged by prospectors filing\non oil claims, and thousands of new\napplications have been made within\nthe past week. The oil strike reported\nseventy miles north of the\nPorcupine Forest Reserve is the\ncause of the excitement. This is\nthe second rush the district has experienced\nthis year, the strike forty\nmiles north in the spring making\nthe town the mecca of prospectors\nfor the summer and falh\nspite of considerable research work,\njust what is cancer is unknown, although\nmuch Is known about what\nit is not, it was pointed out. Caught\nearly enough, cancer is curable in a\nlarge number of cases by means of\na major operation, radium or X-ray\ntreatment, it was said.\nThose who delivered papers on\nvarious aspects of cancer w?re Dr.\njS. R- Karpeles. Dr. Jogeph Mundell.\nDr. T^eon Martel, and Dr. J. Russell\n'Verbrycke. jr. Among those who\ntook part in the discussion were Dr.\nI. B. Nichols. Dr. C. Augustus Simpson,\nDr. E. Y. Simpson, Dr. Frank R.\nHagner.\nThe section on nervous and mental\ndiseases was permanently organized\n?*nd Dr. John M. I,add and Dr. W. R.\nRappaport were elected chairman\nand secretary.\nBOARD OF SrRVRTS AND MAT?\nELECTS OFFICERS.\nThe Roard of Purveys and Maps\nwhich co-ordinates the map makins\nof the country has re-elected O. f.\nMerrill, chairman; Wm. Bowie, vice\nchairman, and C. K. Birdseye. secretary.\nBy special Executive order,\nthe Federal Pewer Commission, the\nArmy Air 8ervice. and the Naval\nAviation Service have been added to\nits membership.\nPROTEST CUT IN CHEMICAL\nWARFARE APPROPRIATION.\nThe cutting of the Chemical Warfaro\nService appropriations from\n$4,500,000 to $1.500.000 has been vigorously\nprotested against fa resolutions\nadopted by the American\nChemical Society committee on national\npolicies. The proposed reduction\nwill seriously cripple this important\nbranch of the army, the\ncommittee says. W. D.\nI 1\nJp Those Battleships\n\\y J. N. DARLING.\n\nV)\nOp i n i o ns\nof Other\nEd i t o r s\nBrief Comment From\nLeading Sew* paper a\nThroughout Nation\n\"Philadelphia I^dgrr\nLincoln forever holds a pi ace all\nhis own in the affections of his\ni-ountrj men because he first loved\nthem. Whatever he did ir the I r<political\nwas done for them and not\nfor a personal ambition. In a profound\nhumility and in a loneliness\nunparalleled he took u|?on himself\nheir burden He asked nothing for\nhimself and he cave all to them.\nlie never forgot IO l,f human\nThere never was a statesman so\ngemiinely democratic.\n<Baltimrw* Sun i\nLincoln was one of humanity's\nprophets, he preached it? gospel, he\nlived for It and he died for it. Kor\nthis reason the world has adopted\nThis American as its own. has recognized\nhim as a kin to all the peoples\nof the earth, as standing pre-eml\nnentl.v for the spirit of justice, love\nand brotherhood. I^ct all Americans\nthank Heaven for Lincoln If\nThis country is to continue Amerl<?n\nin aspiration and in soul. Lincoln\nmust remain one of its presidinc\npatr.otic divinities.\n'New lork Tribune.)\nTile \"Lincoln religion.\" if the\nfeeling aroused by his name can be\nso <a 1 led. spreads over the earih\nIt has no tkigmaa and It has no\nheretics It appeals to the learned\nand to the unlearned. Lincoln has\nbecome one of mankind's common\ndenominators. Humble though rx-alted.\nhe reveals wha, all men ma^\nhe. not in far-off ace* or In after\nlife, but here and now. He Is applied\nChristianity.\nIXew Tort World.I\nCol. Robert G. Ingersol! once\n[complained in a lecture on Lincoln\nthat Washington had already been\ntransformed Into a steel engraving\nand that we no longer knew anything\nabout him as a human being\nIn spite of the fact that there are\nmany men alive who knew Abraham\nLincoln In the flesh. the\nprocess of turning him Into a stee.\nengraving has already advanced ao\nfar that it Is <>oubtful tf the original\nl.incoln will ever be recovered\nNobody would protest more pasf\n1 l than he against the smug\nendeavors of these prigs to iron all\nthe lines out of his shrewd and\nrugged and honest old face, yet protest\nis probably useless. Bv one of\nthose perverse Jokes of historv the\nmost human of American Presidents\nis to be robbed of the characteristics\nthat made him human and i.\nto be presented to posterity as the\n?e\"st. ?f evan